{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"52b2d8a6-c882-4c94-b4b8-9ccfcfa316e4","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_014H4eM1wi6tWG3Lsb4pGEB9","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Answering DSA/.NET question"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_013mv6p37kPWukJM6VRfUSBp","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"ls /tmp/sv-85a8eb7192cc46f89ab0b6073578188b/ 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check for code in working directory","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check for code in working directory"}],"interactionId":"62f1973a-fb07-46f3-9eca-c5be34025038","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nLet me recall the details:\n\nIn .NET 7, Microsoft added `[Obsolete]` warnings for `DSA.Create()` and related DSA APIs on all platforms. Then, in later versions, they went further on macOS specifically.\n\n\nThe root cause is that Apple's native security frameworks dropped DSA support entirely. When .NET on macOS moved away from OpenSSL to Apple's cryptographic libraries, it lost the ability to support DSA since Apple doesn't include it in their modern frameworks. This means that on macOS, calling `DSA.Create()` now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` rather than just issuing a deprecation warning.\n\nI need to be careful here about what I actually know versus what might be speculation about future versions. The user is asking about .NET 10 and .NET 11, which would be versions released after my knowledge cutoff, so I should focus on the documented breaking changes that have already occurred rather than guessing at future behavior.\n\nWhat I can establish: DSA has been marked obsolete since around .NET 7, and on macOS specifically, Apple's native security framework doesn't support DSA at all. .NET's reliance on OpenSSL for DSA operations on macOS has been a compatibility issue that Microsoft has been gradually phasing out. Given the trajectory of these changes and the user's report that `DSA.Create()` throws at runtime on macOS during a .NET 10 to .NET 11 upgrade, this is almost certainly a `PlatformNotSupportedException`.\n\nFor a workaround, if they need to verify legacy DSA signatures, they'd likely need to use a third-party cryptography library like BouncyCastle that can handle DSA independently of the platform's native support. The core issue is that Apple removed DSA from their security frameworks, so .NET stopped supporting it on macOS—those obsolete warnings were the heads-up before the actual removal. I can either use BouncyCastle's managed DSA implementation or migrate to a modern algorithm like ECDSA or Ed25519. Let me check if there's relevant code in the working directory to assess the situation.","outputTokens":1245,"requestId":"680F:132E33:10FE819:1551D32:69FFE2E5"},"id":"df3ea166-5c81-432f-8edd-73d433bd7a24","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:44:35.109Z","parentId":"6e5d3924-f52e-4a8f-a8c5-7861b6c0e7b3"}
